<dl id="n54113a"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n54" href="#n54113a">N54 (VI.B.45)</a>:  <a href="../../FF/fnbs/n54all.htm#n54113a"> 113(a)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> lifted sunbeam (warflag) <small>Orange</small></blockquote> <dd class="well"> <ul class="list-inline" id="n54113a"><li>FW 131.29 </li><li><a href="../../flex/fa/lexfa.htm#n54113a">2010</a> </li><li><a href="../../flex/fa/l39fa.htm#n54113a">1939</a> </li><li><ms href="#n54113a">MS BL 47476a-219</ms> </li><li>JJA 49:461 380515 <a name="fad8" href="../../FF/fdra/fda.htm#fad8">Usage</a> </li><li> <a href="../../flex/fa/fad8.htm#n54113a">Draft: I.6&sect;1.8</a></li> </ul> <blockquote class="sources">We reared the sun-beam of battle; the standard of the king! <br>70n: Fingal&apos;s standard was distinguished by the name of <i>sunbeam</i>; probably on account of its bright colour, and its being studded with gold. <mark>To begin a battle is expressed, in old composition, by <i>lifting of the sun-beam</i>.</mark> <small> James MacPherson, <a name="JMPO2" href="../../FF/fdra/fdex.htm#JMPO2"><cite title="source">The Poems of Ossian</cite></a> (1806), Vol. II, <font size="-1">FINGAL</font> Book IV, 70</small></blockquote> </dd></dl>
